subject_prompt_600:
Kaniv Reservoir is part of the Great Artesian Basin (GAB) that feeds and maintains the fresh water supply of the Great Lakes. It is the largest reservoir on the western shore of Lake Superior. The GAB is a large freshwater catchment formed when runoff from glacial melting on the north bank of the St. Lawrence River, the lower basin (Lake Huron), and Lake Superior meets meltwater in Lake Michigan. The two lakes combine to form the western basin of the Great Lakes. The southern side of Lake Michigan is a series of low-lying land masses of limestone, sandstone, and dolomite; these are called the northern lowlands or central plain. The upper basin (Lake Huron) consists of glacial deposits, mostly mudlites that have been preserved due to their high viscosity and clayey character. The upper reaches of Lake Huron extend into the Great Lakes, while parts of Lake Superior penetrate the eastern boundary of the Great Lakes. Lakes Superior and Huron join in the central basin to form the Great Lakes system. Lake Superior and Huron discharge into the Gulf of Mexico (which is not part of the Great Lakes system). The total drainage area of the Great Lakes is approximately 1,000,000 km2 (454,000 sq mi). Only one-third of this area receives precipitation, with the rest being covered by the glaciers of the Alps.

References

Baker-Davies, A., J.M. Gorman, and E.C. Riddle. 1999. Freshwater Systems in the Greater Canadian Prairies. Ottawa, Canada: National Research Council of Canada.

Fletcher, D.W. 2006. Water Quality Monitoring in the Great Lakes Basin: Lake Ontario. In J. F. Gorman, R.S. McBride, T.L. Martin, A.O. Zwemer, C.J. Miller, and P.R. Goss, eds., Handbook of Freshwater Management of the Great Lakes Basin: Proceedings of the Fourth International Symposium, Water Quality Assessment and Management in the Upper Great Lakes Region, June 22–24, 2004, Toronto, Canada, pp. 837–852.
